{"title_page": "Utica Blue Sox", "text_new": "<!-- Infobox begins -->\n{{Infobox Minor League Baseball\n| name = Utica Blue Sox\n| firstseason = 1939 \n| lastseason = 2001\n| allyears = 1939\u20131950 and 1977\u20132001\n| city = Utica, New York\n| logo = \n| caplogo = \n| past class level = {{plainlist|\n*Short Season-A (1977\u20132001)\n*Class A (1943\u20131950)\n*Class C (1939\u20131942)\n}}\n| league = \n| conference = \n| division = \n| past league = {{plainlist|\n*[[New York\u2013Penn League]] (1977\u20132001)\n*[[Eastern League (baseball)|Eastern League]] (1944\u20131950)\n*[[Canadian\u2013American League|Can-Am League]] (1939\u20131942) \n}}\n| pastmajorleague = {{plainlist|\n*[[Florida Marlins]] (1996\u20132001)\n*[[Boston Red Sox]] (1993\u20131995)\n*[[Chicago White Sox]] (1988\u20131992)\n*[[Philadelphia Phillies]] (1986\u20131987)\n*Co-op (1981\u20131985)\n*[[Toronto Blue Jays]] (1977\u20131980) \n*Philadelphia Phillies (1943\u20131950)\n*[[Detroit Tigers]] (1940)\n*[[Boston Braves (baseball)|Boston Braves]] (1939)\n}}\n| pastnames = {{plainlist|\n*Utica Blue Sox  (1997\u20132001)\n*Utica Blue Marlins (1996)\n*Utica Blue Sox  (1981\u20131995) \n*Utica Blue Jays (1977\u20131980)\n*Utica Blue Sox (1944\u20131950) \n*Utica Braves (1939\u20131943)\n}}\n| pastparks = {{plainlist|\n*[[Donovan Stadium at Murnane Field|Donovan Stadium]] (1981\u20132001)\n*McConnell Field (1944\u20131950)\n}}\n| classchamps = \n| leaguechamps = '''2''' (1947, 1983)\n| conferencechamps =  \n| divisionchamps = \n}}<!-- Infobox ends -->\n\nThe '''Utica Blue Sox''' was the name of two [[Minor League Baseball|minor league baseball]] teams based in [[Utica, New York]].\n\nIn the 2010s, the ''Utica Blue Sox'' is the name of a collegiate wooden bat baseball team of the [[Perfect Game Collegiate Baseball League]] based in [[New York State]]. <ref>http://pgcbl.com/schedule/utica/</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Picciuto BlueSox.jpg|thumb|right]]\n[[File:Ashburn-Picciuto.jpg|thumb|left|[[Richie Ashburn]] and [[Nick Picciuto]] Utica Blue Sox 1945]]\n\n===Previous baseball history===\nUtica's first baseball team took the field in 1878.  The city fielded a team in the [[New York State League (1885\u20131917)|New York State League]] from 1899\u20131917, then was without professional baseball until [[1939 in baseball|1939]], except for one year, [[1924 in baseball|1924]], when the '''Utica Utes,''' a member of an earlier edition of the [[New York\u2013Pennsylvania League (1923\u201337)|New York\u2013Pennsylvania League]], moved to [[Oneonta, New York]], in midseason.\n\n===The first Blue Sox team===\nThe first Blue Sox team can be traced to the  '''Utica Braves''' of the Class C [[Canadian\u2013American League]], formed when the former Auburn Bouleys were moved to Utica by Amby McConnell and Father Harold Martin. The Utica Braves were initially a [[Boston Braves (baseball)|Boston Braves]] [[farm team]] in 1939 and kept the nickname through 1942. The Braves were also affiliated with the [[Detroit Tigers]] in 1941 and the [[Springfield Rifles (baseball)|Springfield Rifles]] in 1942.<ref>{{Cite web|title = 1943 Utica Braves Statistics -- Minor Leagues  {{!}} Baseball-Reference.com|url = https://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/team.cgi?id=b7afb2a6|website = Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate = 2015-07-22}}</ref>\n\nIn [[1943 in baseball|1943]], Utica moved up to the Class A [[Eastern League (baseball)|Eastern League]] and became an affiliate of the [[Philadelphia Phillies]]. The nickname Blue Sox dates to [[1944 in baseball|1944]] when their parent team was unofficially called the \"Philadelphia Blue Jays\".  The Blue Sox of the 1940s played in a ballpark in the northern part of the city called McConnell Field, which was named after the team owner and former pro player from Utica.\n\nMany of the Blue Sox players of the 1940s later became the ''Whiz Kids'' of the [[1950 in baseball|1950]] [[National League]] champion  Phillies. \n\nFuture Philadelphia stars such as [[National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum|Hall of Famer]] [[Richie Ashburn]], who came to Utica as a [[catcher]] but within a month was moved to [[center fielder|center field]] by his [[manager (baseball)|manager]], [[Eddie Sawyer]], to utilize his speed. \n\nOthers, including [[Stan Lopata]] and [[Granny Hamner]], all took the field for both Utica and Philadelphia during the late 1940s.\n\nEddie Sawyer, manager of the Blue Sox in 1945 and 1947 and later for seven more years in Philadelphia, once said, \"We had great ballclubs in a bad ballpark.\" Ashburn recalled  the peculiar way the field was laid out, with center field to the west. \"The sun would set over it\", he once said. \"I never got a hit up there in the first five innings in 150 games, and I still hit .300.\"{{Citation needed|date=August 2013}}\n\n[[Murnane Field]] was considered one of the worst baseball layouts in the NY-P league with right field sloping downhill drastically by the time it hit the fence.\n\n===Second Blue Sox team===\nThe name Blue Sox was resurrected in the Short-Season A classification [[New York\u2013Penn League]]. \n\nA new NY-P franchise began in 1977 as the Utica Blue Jays, playing at Murnane Field, being the first affiliate in the Toronto Blue Jays organization, from 1977\u20131980. That team included Toronto's first ever draft pick, Tom Goffena. The line up also included future major leaguers Jesse Barfield, David Wells and Paul Hodgson. \n\nToronto withdrew their affiliation after the 1980 season and the club played as an independent, under the name Blue Sox, from 1981 through 1983. The ownership of that team included Miles Wolff (Durham Bulls), actor/writer Brian Doyle Murray and his brother, comedian Bill Murray. Bill Murray sang the national anthem for the Blue Sox 1981 home opener. The independent Utica Blue Sox won the NY-P championship in 1983.\n\nThe team became an affiliate with the [[Philadelphia Phillies]] from 1986\u20131987, the [[Chicago White Sox]] from 1988\u201392 and the [[Boston Red Sox]] from 1993\u20131995. In 1996 the team became affiliated with the [[Florida Marlins]] and were renamed the '''Utica Marlins'''; however, the team was renamed the Blue Sox the very next season. Among the notable players who were once Utica Blue Sox players; Larry Walker, Miguel Cabrera, Adrian Gonzales, Andy Ashby, Jason Grimsley and Esteban Beltre.\n\nBy the end of the 2001 season, the city needed a standard level ball park and Donovan Stadium at Murnane Field was in need of renovations and repairs in order to keep the Blue Sox team in the league. On February 7, 2002, [[Cal Ripken, Jr.]] and  the Ripken Professional Baseball Association purchased the Blue Sox and moved the club to [[Aberdeen, Maryland]], where it became the [[Aberdeen IronBirds]].\n\nFor a time in the late 1980s, [[Morganna|Morganna the Kissing Bandit]] owned a share of the Blue Sox.<ref name=\"York\">{{cite news|last=York|first=Marty|title=Morganna riding the buss to success in the minor leagues|work=The Globe and Mail|date=1989-06-27}}</ref>\n\n==In media==\nAcclaimed author and journalist [[Roger Kahn]] (''The Boys of Summer'') wrote about his year as a part owner of the team for the 1983 championship season. The book, ''Good Enough to Dream,'' was published in 1985.\n\n==Notable Alumni==\n\n{{div col|colwidth=25em}}\n\n===[[Baseball Hall of Fame]] alumni===\n\n* [[Richie Ashburn]] (1945) Inducted, 1995\n\n* [[Larry Walker]] (1985) 5 x MLB All-Star; 3 x NL Batting Title (1998-1999, 2001);  1997 NL Most Valuable Player; Inducted, 2020\n\n===Notable alumni===\n\n* [[Andy Ashby]] (1987) 2 x MLB All-Star\n\n* [[Jesse Barfield]] (1977) MLB All-Star\n\n* [[Ken Brett]] (1985) MLB All-Star\n\n* [[Miguel Cabrera]] (2000) 11 x MLB All-Star; 4 x  MLB Batting Title (2011-2013, 2015); 2012 AL Triple Crown; 2 x AL Most Valuable Player (2012-2013)\n\n* [[Mike Cameron]] (1992) MLB All-Star\n\n* [[Ray Durham]] (1991) 2 x MLB All-Star\n\n* [[Ross Gload]] (1997)\n\n* [[Jason Grimsley]] (1986)\n\n* [[Granny Hamner]] (1945) 3 x MLB All-Star\n\n* [[Willie Jones (baseball)|Willie Jones]] (1948) 2 x MLB All-Star\n\n* [[Fred Kendall]] (1992)\n\n* [[Stan Lopata]] (1945) 2 x MLB All-Star\n\n* [[Chuck McElroy]] (1986)\n\n* [[Steve Ridzik]] (1949)\n\n*[[Wally Schang]] (1943)\n\n* [[Scott Service]] (1986)\n\n* [[Tony Taylor (baseball) |Tony Taylor]] (1986-1987) 2 x MLB All-Star\n\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book |title=Good Enough to Dream |last=Kahn |first=Roger|authorlink= |coauthors= |year=1985|publisher=Doubleday|location=Garden City, New York |isbn=0-8032-7779-2 |page= |pages= |url= |accessdate=}}\n\n==External links==\n*Lloyd Johnson and Miles Wolff, editors. ''The Encyclopedia of Minor League Baseball'', 1997 edition. Durham, North Carolina: [[Baseball America]].\n*[http://www.frontiernet.net/~rochballparks/utica/donovan.htm Photographs of Donovan Stadium (Murnane Field), former home of the Utica Blue Sox of the NY-P League \u2013 ''Rochester Area Ballparks'']\n\n{{New York \u2013 Penn League |state=collapsed}}\n{{New York-Pennsylvania League (1923-1937) |state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Baseball teams established in 1939]]\n[[Category:Sports clubs disestablished in 2001]]\n[[Category:Defunct New York\u2013Penn League teams]]\n[[Category:Defunct Eastern League baseball teams]]\n[[Category:Boston Braves minor league affiliates]]\n[[Category:Boston Red Sox minor league affiliates]]\n[[Category:Chicago White Sox minor league affiliates]]\n[[Category:Detroit Tigers minor league affiliates]]\n[[Category:Miami Marlins minor league affiliates]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia Phillies minor league affiliates]]\n[[Category:Toronto Blue Jays minor league affiliates]]\n[[Category:Defunct baseball teams in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:1939 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:2001 disestablishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Utica, New York]]\n", "text_old": "<!-- Infobox begins -->\n{{Infobox Minor League Baseball\n| name = Utica Blue Sox\n| firstseason = 1939 \n| lastseason = 2001\n| allyears = 1939\u20131950 and 1977\u20132001\n| city = Utica, New York\n| logo = \n| caplogo = \n| past class level = {{plainlist|\n*Short Season-A (1977\u20132001)\n*Class A (1943\u20131950)\n*Class C (1939\u20131942)\n}}\n| league = \n| conference = \n| division = \n| past league = {{plainlist|\n*[[New York\u2013Penn League]] (1977\u20132001)\n*[[Eastern League (baseball)|Eastern League]] (1944\u20131950)\n*[[Canadian\u2013American League|Can-Am League]] (1939\u20131942) \n}}\n| pastmajorleague = {{plainlist|\n*[[Florida Marlins]] (1996\u20132001)\n*[[Boston Red Sox]] (1993\u20131995)\n*[[Chicago White Sox]] (1988\u20131992)\n*[[Philadelphia Phillies]] (1986\u20131987)\n*Co-op (1981\u20131985)\n*[[Toronto Blue Jays]] (1977\u20131980) \n*Philadelphia Phillies (1943\u20131950)\n*[[Detroit Tigers]] (1940)\n*[[Boston Braves (baseball)|Boston Braves]] (1939)\n}}\n| pastnames = {{plainlist|\n*Utica Blue Sox  (1997\u20132001)\n*Utica Blue Marlins (1996)\n*Utica Blue Sox  (1981\u20131995) \n*Utica Blue Jays (1977\u20131980)\n*Utica Blue Sox (1944\u20131950) \n*Utica Braves (1939\u20131943)\n}}\n| pastparks = {{plainlist|\n*[[Donovan Stadium at Murnane Field|Donovan Stadium]] (1981\u20132001)\n*McConnell Field (1944\u20131950)\n}}\n| classchamps = \n| leaguechamps = '''2''' (1947, 1983)\n| conferencechamps =  \n| divisionchamps = \n}}<!-- Infobox ends -->\n\nThe '''Utica Blue Sox''' was the name of two [[Minor League Baseball|minor league baseball]] teams based in [[Utica, New York]].\n\nIn the 2010s, the ''Utica Blue Sox'' is the name of a collegiate wooden bat baseball team of the [[Perfect Game Collegiate Baseball League]] based in [[New York State]]. <ref>http://pgcbl.com/schedule/utica/</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Picciuto BlueSox.jpg|thumb|right]]\n[[File:Ashburn-Picciuto.jpg|thumb|left|[[Richie Ashburn]] and [[Nick Picciuto]] Utica Blue Sox 1945]]\n\n===Previous baseball history===\nUtica's first baseball team took the field in 1878.  The city fielded a team in the [[New York State League (1885\u20131917)|New York State League]] from 1899\u20131917, then was without professional baseball until [[1939 in baseball|1939]], except for one year, [[1924 in baseball|1924]], when the '''Utica Utes,''' a member of an earlier edition of the [[New York\u2013Pennsylvania League (1923\u201337)|New York\u2013Pennsylvania League]], moved to [[Oneonta, New York]], in midseason.\n\n===The first Blue Sox team===\nThe first Blue Sox team can be traced to the  '''Utica Braves''' of the Class C [[Canadian\u2013American League]], formed when the former Auburn Bouleys were moved to Utica by Amby McConnell and Father Harold Martin. The Utica Braves were initially a [[Boston Braves (baseball)|Boston Braves]] [[farm team]] in 1939 and kept the nickname through 1942. The Braves were also affiliated with the [[Detroit Tigers]] in 1941 and the [[Springfield Rifles (baseball)|Springfield Rifles]] in 1942.<ref>{{Cite web|title = 1943 Utica Braves Statistics -- Minor Leagues  {{!}} Baseball-Reference.com|url = https://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/team.cgi?id=b7afb2a6|website = Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate = 2015-07-22}}</ref>\n\nIn [[1943 in baseball|1943]], Utica moved up to the Class A [[Eastern League (baseball)|Eastern League]] and became an affiliate of the [[Philadelphia Phillies]]. The nickname Blue Sox dates to [[1944 in baseball|1944]] when their parent team was unofficially called the \"Philadelphia Blue Jays\".  The Blue Sox of the 1940s played in a ballpark in the northern part of the city called McConnell Field, which was named after the team owner and former pro player from Utica.\n\nMany of the Blue Sox players of the 1940s later became the ''Whiz Kids'' of the [[1950 in baseball|1950]] [[National League]] champion  Phillies. \n\nFuture Philadelphia stars such as [[National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum|Hall of Famer]] [[Richie Ashburn]], who came to Utica as a [[catcher]] but within a month was moved to [[center fielder|center field]] by his [[manager (baseball)|manager]], [[Eddie Sawyer]], to utilize his speed. \n\nOthers, including [[Stan Lopata]] and [[Granny Hamner]], all took the field for both Utica and Philadelphia during the late 1940s.\n\nEddie Sawyer, manager of the Blue Sox in 1945 and 1947 and later for seven more years in Philadelphia, once said, \"We had great ballclubs in a bad ballpark.\" Ashburn recalled  the peculiar way the field was laid out, with center field to the west. \"The sun would set over it\", he once said. \"I never got a hit up there in the first five innings in 150 games, and I still hit .300.\"{{Citation needed|date=August 2013}}\n\n[[Murnane Field]] was considered one of the worst baseball layouts in the NY-P league with right field sloping downhill drastically by the time it hit the fence.\n\n===Second Blue Sox team===\nThe name Blue Sox was resurrected in the Short-Season A classification [[New York\u2013Penn League]]. \n\nA new NY-P franchise began in 1977 as the Utica Blue Jays, playing at Murnane Field, being the first affiliate in the Toronto Blue Jays organization, from 1977\u20131980. That team included Toronto's first ever draft pick, Tom Goffena. The line up also included future major leaguers Jesse Barfield, David Wells and Paul Hodgson. \n\nToronto withdrew their affiliation after the 1980 season and the club played as an independent, under the name Blue Sox, from 1981 through 1983. The ownership of that team included Miles Wolff (Durham Bulls), actor/writer Brian Doyle Murray and his brother, comedian Bill Murray. Bill Murray sang the national anthem for the Blue Sox 1981 home opener. The independent Utica Blue Sox won the NY-P championship in 1983.\n\nThe team became an affiliate with the [[Philadelphia Phillies]] from 1986\u20131987, the [[Chicago White Sox]] from 1988\u201392 and the [[Boston Red Sox]] from 1993\u20131995. In 1996 the team became affiliated with the [[Florida Marlins]] and were renamed the '''Utica Marlins'''; however, the team was renamed the Blue Sox the very next season. Among the notable players who were once Utica Blue Sox players; Larry Walker, Miguel Cabrera, Adrian Gonzales, Andy Ashby, Jason Grimsley and Esteban Beltre.\n\nBy the end of the 2001 season, the city needed a standard level ball park and Donovan Stadium at Murnane Field, was in need of renovations and repairs in order to keep the Blue Sox team in the league. On February 7, 2002, [[Cal Ripken, Jr.]] and  the Ripken Professional Baseball Association purchased the Blue Sox and moved the club to [[Aberdeen, Maryland]], where it became the [[Aberdeen IronBirds]].\n\nFor a time in the late 1980s, [[Morganna|Morganna the Kissing Bandit]] owned a share of the Blue Sox.<ref name=\"York\">{{cite news|last=York|first=Marty|title=Morganna riding the buss to success in the minor leagues|work=The Globe and Mail|date=1989-06-27}}</ref>\n\n==In media==\nAcclaimed author and journalist [[Roger Kahn]] (''The Boys of Summer'') wrote about his year as a part owner of the team for the 1983 championship season. The book, ''Good Enough to Dream,'' was published in 1985.\n\n==Notable Alumni==\n\n{{div col|colwidth=25em}}\n\n===[[Baseball Hall of Fame]] alumni===\n\n* [[Richie Ashburn]] (1945) Inducted, 1995\n\n* [[Larry Walker]] (1985) 5 x MLB All-Star; 3 x NL Batting Title (1998-1999, 2001);  1997 NL Most Valuable Player; Inducted, 2020\n\n===Notable alumni===\n\n* [[Andy Ashby]] (1987) 2 x MLB All-Star\n\n* [[Jesse Barfield]] (1977) MLB All-Star\n\n* [[Ken Brett]] (1985) MLB All-Star\n\n* [[Miguel Cabrera]] (2000) 11 x MLB All-Star; 4 x  MLB Batting Title (2011-2013, 2015); 2012 AL Triple Crown; 2 x AL Most Valuable Player (2012-2013)\n\n* [[Mike Cameron]] (1992) MLB All-Star\n\n* [[Ray Durham]] (1991) 2 x MLB All-Star\n\n* [[Ross Gload]] (1997)\n\n* [[Jason Grimsley]] (1986)\n\n* [[Granny Hamner]] (1945) 3 x MLB All-Star\n\n* [[Willie Jones (baseball)|Willie Jones]] (1948) 2 x MLB All-Star\n\n* [[Fred Kendall]] (1992)\n\n* [[Stan Lopata]] (1945) 2 x MLB All-Star\n\n* [[Chuck McElroy]] (1986)\n\n* [[Steve Ridzik]] (1949)\n\n*[[Wally Schang]] (1943)\n\n* [[Scott Service]] (1986)\n\n* [[Tony Taylor (baseball) |Tony Taylor]] (1986-1987) 2 x MLB All-Star\n\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book |title=Good Enough to Dream |last=Kahn |first=Roger|authorlink= |coauthors= |year=1985|publisher=Doubleday|location=Garden City, New York |isbn=0-8032-7779-2 |page= |pages= |url= |accessdate=}}\n\n==External links==\n*Lloyd Johnson and Miles Wolff, editors. ''The Encyclopedia of Minor League Baseball'', 1997 edition. Durham, North Carolina: [[Baseball America]].\n*[http://www.frontiernet.net/~rochballparks/utica/donovan.htm Photographs of Donovan Stadium (Murnane Field), former home of the Utica Blue Sox of the NY-P League \u2013 ''Rochester Area Ballparks'']\n\n{{New York \u2013 Penn League |state=collapsed}}\n{{New York-Pennsylvania League (1923-1937) |state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Baseball teams established in 1939]]\n[[Category:Sports clubs disestablished in 2001]]\n[[Category:Defunct New York\u2013Penn League teams]]\n[[Category:Defunct Eastern League baseball teams]]\n[[Category:Boston Braves minor league affiliates]]\n[[Category:Boston Red Sox minor league affiliates]]\n[[Category:Chicago White Sox minor league affiliates]]\n[[Category:Detroit Tigers minor league affiliates]]\n[[Category:Miami Marlins minor league affiliates]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia Phillies minor league affiliates]]\n[[Category:Toronto Blue Jays minor league affiliates]]\n[[Category:Defunct baseball teams in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:1939 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:2001 disestablishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Utica, New York]]\n", "name_user": "EdMcCorduck", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSecond Blue Sox team:changed text \"Field,\" in fifth paragraph to \"Field\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Utica_Blue_Sox"}
{"title_page": "Marine Corps Musician Enlistment Option Program", "text_new": "{{short description|Organizaitonal body for Marine bands}}\n\n[[File:2nd_Marine_Aircraft_Wing_performs_at_Yankee_Stadium_101010-M-DO926-006.jpg|thumb|The [[2nd Marine Aircraft Wing Band]] performing at [[Yankee Stadium]]. The band is one of ten field bands sponsored by the program.]]\nThe '''Marine Corps Musician Enlistment Option Program (MEOP)''' is the central organized body overseeing the active-duty [[military bands]] of the [[United States Marine Corps]]. Marine Corps field bands can be found in the [[Southeast United States]], [[Southern California]], and the [[Pacific]]-[[Asia]] region.\u00a0 While serving with their bands, Marines perform throughout the continental United States and travel internationally to locations ranging from [[Beijing]] to [[Paris]]. Thses units take part in activities such as retirement ceremonies, the Marine Corps Birthday Ball, funerals, [[Change of command|change of commands]], and civil/[[military parades]]. It is one of two music programs in the [[Department of the Navy]], with the other being [[Fleet Band Activities]].\n\n== Overview of Marine bands ==\n[[File:USMC-02129.jpg|thumb|The Drum Major of the [[United States Marine Band]] leading the band during a [[military parade]].]]\nAll USMC field bands are required to perform as a range of ensembles such as ceremonial band and [[big band]]. Additionally, the bands are required to maintain engage in regular Marine training and uphold the standards for Marines.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marines.com/videos/-/video-library/detail/video_meop|title=Musician Enlistment Option Program (MEOP)|website=marines.com|publisher=U.S. Marine Corps|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151206171139/http://www.marines.com/videos/-/video-library/detail/video_meop|archive-date=6 December 2015|accessdate=15 November 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> When deployed on duty, Marine bands serve as provisional rifle platoons and rear area security for the commanding officer.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Lacy|first1=Linda|title=We are Marines!: World War I to the Present|date=2004|isbn=1-59975-887-3|pages=292\u2013293}}</ref> Individual musicians can also request for augmentation into combat arms units.<ref>https://www.mcrc.marines.mil/1stmcd/Unit-Home/Music/</ref> The first female musician to be recruited through the program was [[Marine Corps Recruiting Command|recruited]] in [[California]] in 2017.<ref>https://www.whs.mil/News/News-Display/Article/2132392/defining-worth-through-music-and-the-marine-corps/</ref>\n\n=== Training ===\nAll Marine musicians are required to audition for a placement in the music program. They then gi through [[United States Marine Corps Recruit Training|recruit training]] at one of two Marine bases. Upon graduation, musicians attend the [[United States Navy School of Music]] in [[Virginia]].<ref>https://www.marines.com/becoming-a-marine/enlisted/musician-enlistment-option-program.html</ref> The first Marine Corps students were enrolled in the school of music in 1947. During their stay at the school, they attend a six-month basic music course, which involves weekly private instrumental instruction, ear training, as well as [[music theory]]. After their training is complete, Marine musicians are then transferred to their bands for permanent duty.\u00a0\n\n== List of Marine bands ==\nThr [[United States Marine Band]] is the USMC's central band and the seniormost band in the USMC. It is a [[List of United States military premier ensembles|premier ensemble]], which means that it's duties are of a high natures and includes duties in [[Washington D.C.]], the national capital. The [[United States Marine Drum and Bugle Corps]] is another USMC premier ensemble based in the national capital.\n\nThere are also 10 field bands are maintained by Marine wings/divisions:<ref>https://www.defense.gov/Explore/News/Article/Article/694827/face-of-defense-marines-follow-passion-for-music-through-enlistment-program/</ref><ref>[https://www.1stmardiv.marines.mil/Units/1ST-DIV-BAND/FAQ/ FAQS]</ref>\n\n* Quantico Marine Corps Band ([[Quantico, Virginia]])\n* Parris Island Marine Band ([[Parris Island, South Carolina]])\n* Marine Corps Band San Diego ([[San Diego, California]])\n* [[1st Marine Division Band]] ([[Camp Pendleton, California]])\n* 2nd Marine Division Band ([[Camp Lejeune, North Carolina]])\n* [[2nd Marine Aircraft Wing Band]] ([[Cherry Point, North Carolina]])\n* 3rd Marine Aircraft Wing Band ([[Miramar, San Diego]], [[California]])\n* Marine Corps Forces, Pacific Band ([[Marine Corps Base Hawaii]])\n* [[III Marine Expeditionary Force Band]] ([[Camp Courtney]], [[Japan]])\n* [[Marine Forces Reserve]] Band ([[New Orleans, Louisiana]])\n\nThe ''[[ad hoc]]'' [[West Coast]] Composite Band and [[East Coast]] Composite Band is also maintained. The former is often avaliable at the [[Rose Parade]]<ref>https://www.hqmc.marines.mil/News/News-Article-Display/Article/551742/west-coast-composite-band-marches-in-114th-tournament-of-roses-parade/</ref> in [[California]] while the latter often performs at the [[Macy's Thanksgiving Day Parade]] in [[New York City|New York]]. Bands not currently in service have included the [[Marine Corps Air Ground Combat Center Twentynine Palms]] Band and the III Marine Amphibious Force Band.\n\n== Other Marine bands ==\n\n=== Leatherneck Pipes and Drums ===\n[[File:US_Navy_100530-N-1831S-080_The_Leatherneck_Pipes_and_Drums_practice_before_a_Sunset_Parade_on_the_flight_deck_of_USS_Iwo_Jima_(LHD_7).jpg|thumb|The Leatherneck Pipes and Drums rehearse prior to a Sunset Parade on the flight deck of the ''[[USS Iwo Jima]]''.]] \nThe Leatherneck Pipes and Drums is a private military [[pipe band]] that supports military ceremonies in the USMC. Being a private unit, it is composed of mostly former USMC personnel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/?id=TP7RV0_verQC&pg=RA8-PA16&dq=Leatherneck+Pipes+and+Drums#v=onepage&q=Leatherneck%20Pipes%20and%20Drums&f=false|title=Navigator: The U.S. Coast Guard Auxiliary Magazine|year=2002}}</ref> It was formed in 1991 from Marine veterans who lived in parts of the [[Northeastern United States]] and was based on the original Marine pipe band based in [[Derry, Northern Ireland]] during the [[Second World War]]. The official tartan of the unit is the Leatherneck Tartan which is only used by the pipes and drums due to the fact that the USMC has never formally adopted a military tartan.<ref>https://www.poconorecord.com/article/20070313/holidays01/70313008</ref><ref>https://alexismalcolmkilts.com/us-military-tartans</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.militarybagpiper.org/marine_bagpiping|title=Marine Bagpiping - U.S. Military Bagpiper Network}}</ref> During many of its ceremonies, the band performs special arrangements of the ''[[Star Spangled Banner]]'' and ''The [[Marines' Hymn]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.leatherneck.com/forums/archive/index.php/t-10628.html|title=Marine Hymn (Bagpipes) &#91;Archive&#93; - Marine Corps - USMC Community}}</ref> When at an official ceremony, all members of the unit wear a modified [[Uniforms of the United States Marine Corps|Blue Dress \"A\"]] uniform which is augmented with a [[Glengarry]] cap and a [[kilt]] that is patterned in the leatherneck [[tartan]]. Keeping in [[Highland]]/Scottish tradition, the drum major wears [[feather bonnet]] instead of a Glengarry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.courant.com/sdut-10000-marines-80000-spectators-expected-saturday-2003oct19-story.html?outputType=amp|title=10,000 Marines, 80,000 spectators expected Saturday for parade}}</ref>\n\n=== Band of America's Few ===\nCreated in 2009, the Band of America\u2019s Few is a nonprofit USMC musical unit organized by Marine retirees and veterans. Most of the musicians were assigned to the Marine Corps field bands in the past.<ref>http://bandofamericasfew.com/about-2/</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[United States military bands]]\n* [[Fleet Band Activities]]\n* [[List of United States Air Force bands]]\n* [[Navy bands in Canada]]\n* [[Royal Marines Band Service]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{US Marine Corps navbox}}\n{{United States military bands|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Bands of the United States Marine Corps]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Organizaitonal body for Marine bands}}\n\n[[File:2nd_Marine_Aircraft_Wing_performs_at_Yankee_Stadium_101010-M-DO926-006.jpg|thumb|The [[2nd Marine Aircraft Wing Band]] performing at [[Yankee Stadium]]. The band is one of ten field bands sponsored by the program.]]\nThe '''Marine Corps Musician Enlistment Option Program (MEOP)''' is the central organized body overseeing the active-duty [[military bands]] of the [[United States Marine Corps]]. Marine Corps field bands can be found in the [[Southeast United States]], [[Southern California]], and the [[Pacific]]-[[Asia]] region.\u00a0 While serving with their bands, Marines perform throughout the continental United States and travel internationally to locations ranging from [[Beijing]] to [[Paris]]. Thses units take part in activities such as retirement ceremonies, the Marine Corps Birthday Ball, funerals, [[Change of command|change of commands]], and civil/[[military parades]]. It is one of two music programs in the [[Department of the Navy]], with the other being [[Fleet Band Activities]].\n\n== Overview of Marine bands ==\n[[File:USMC-02129.jpg|thumb|The Drum Major of the [[United States Marine Band]] leading the band during a [[military parade]].]]\nAll USMC field bands are required to perform as a range of ensembles such as ceremonial band and [[big band]]. Additionally, the bands are required to maintain engage in regular Marine training and uphold the standards for Marines.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marines.com/videos/-/video-library/detail/video_meop|title=Musician Enlistment Option Program (MEOP)|website=marines.com|publisher=U.S. Marine Corps|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151206171139/http://www.marines.com/videos/-/video-library/detail/video_meop|archive-date=6 December 2015|accessdate=15 November 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> When deployed on duty, Marine bands serve as provisional rifle platoons and rear area security for the commanding officer.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Lacy|first1=Linda|title=We are Marines!: World War I to the Present|date=2004|isbn=1-59975-887-3|pages=292\u2013293}}</ref> Individual musicians can also request for augmentation into combat arms units.<ref>https://www.mcrc.marines.mil/1stmcd/Unit-Home/Music/</ref> The first female musician to be recruited through the program was [[Marine Corps Recruiting Command|recruited]] in [[California]] in 2017.<ref>https://www.whs.mil/News/News-Display/Article/2132392/defining-worth-through-music-and-the-marine-corps/</ref>\n\n=== Training ===\nAll Marine musicians are required to audition for a placement in the music program. They then gi through [[United States Marine Corps Recruit Training|recruit training]] at one of two Marine bases. Upon graduation, musicians attend the [[United States Navy School of Music]] in [[Virginia]].<ref>https://www.marines.com/becoming-a-marine/enlisted/musician-enlistment-option-program.html</ref> The first Marine Corps students were enrolled in the school of music in 1947. During their stay at the school, they attend a six-month basic music course, which involves weekly private instrumental instruction, ear training, as well as [[music theory]]. After their training is complete, Marine musicians are then transferred to their bands for permanent duty.\u00a0\n\n== List of Marine bands ==\nThr [[United States Marine Band]] is the USMC's central band and the seniormost band in the USMC. It is a [[List of United States military premier ensembles|premier ensemble]], which means that it's duties are of a high natures and includes duties in [[Washington D.C.]], the national capital. The [[United States Marine Drum and Bugle Corps]] is another USMC premier ensemble based in the national capital.\n\nThere are also 10 field bands are maintained by Marine wings/divisions:<ref>https://www.defense.gov/Explore/News/Article/Article/694827/face-of-defense-marines-follow-passion-for-music-through-enlistment-program/</ref><ref>[https://www.1stmardiv.marines.mil/Units/1ST-DIV-BAND/FAQ/ FAQS]</ref>\n\n* Quantico Marine Corps Band ([[Quantico, Virginia]])\n* Parris Island Marine Band ([[Parris Island, South Carolina]])\n* Marine Corps Band San Diego ([[San Diego, California]])\n* [[1st Marine Division Band]] ([[Camp Pendleton, California]])\n* 2nd Marine Division Band ([[Camp Lejeune, North Carolina]])\n* [[2nd Marine Aircraft Wing Band]] ([[Cherry Point, North Carolina]])\n* 3rd Marine Aircraft Wing Band ([[Miramar, San Diego]], [[California]])\n* Marine Corps Forces, Pacific Band ([[Marine Corps Base Hawaii]])\n* [[III Marine Expeditionary Force Band]] ([[Camp Courtney]], [[Japan]])\n* [[Marine Forces Reserve]] Band ([[New Orleans, Louisiana]])\n\nThe ''[[ad hoc]]'' [[West Coast]] Composite Band and [[East Coast]] Composite Band is also maintained. The former is often avaliable at the [[Rose Parade]]<ref>https://www.hqmc.marines.mil/News/News-Article-Display/Article/551742/west-coast-composite-band-marches-in-114th-tournament-of-roses-parade/</ref> in [[California]] while the latter often performs at the [[Macy's Thanksgiving Day Parade]] in [[New York]]. Bands not currently in service have included the [[Marine Corps Air Ground Combat Center Twentynine Palms]] Band and the III Marine Amphibious Force Band.\n\n== Other Marine bands ==\n\n=== Leatherneck Pipes and Drums ===\n[[File:US_Navy_100530-N-1831S-080_The_Leatherneck_Pipes_and_Drums_practice_before_a_Sunset_Parade_on_the_flight_deck_of_USS_Iwo_Jima_(LHD_7).jpg|thumb|The Leatherneck Pipes and Drums rehearse prior to a Sunset Parade on the flight deck of the ''[[USS Iwo Jima]]''.]] \nThe Leatherneck Pipes and Drums is a private military [[pipe band]] that supports military ceremonies in the USMC. Being a private unit, it is composed of mostly former USMC personnel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/?id=TP7RV0_verQC&pg=RA8-PA16&dq=Leatherneck+Pipes+and+Drums#v=onepage&q=Leatherneck%20Pipes%20and%20Drums&f=false|title=Navigator: The U.S. Coast Guard Auxiliary Magazine|year=2002}}</ref> It was formed in 1991 from Marine veterans who lived in parts of the [[Northeastern United States]] and was based on the original Marine pipe band based in [[Derry, Northern Ireland]] during the [[Second World War]]. The official tartan of the unit is the Leatherneck Tartan which is only used by the pipes and drums due to the fact that the USMC has never formally adopted a military tartan.<ref>https://www.poconorecord.com/article/20070313/holidays01/70313008</ref><ref>https://alexismalcolmkilts.com/us-military-tartans</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.militarybagpiper.org/marine_bagpiping|title=Marine Bagpiping - U.S. Military Bagpiper Network}}</ref> During many of its ceremonies, the band performs special arrangements of the ''[[Star Spangled Banner]]'' and ''The [[Marines' Hymn]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.leatherneck.com/forums/archive/index.php/t-10628.html|title=Marine Hymn (Bagpipes) &#91;Archive&#93; - Marine Corps - USMC Community}}</ref> When at an official ceremony, all members of the unit wear a modified [[Uniforms of the United States Marine Corps|Blue Dress \"A\"]] uniform which is augmented with a [[Glengarry]] cap and a [[kilt]] that is patterned in the leatherneck [[tartan]]. Keeping in [[Highland]]/Scottish tradition, the drum major wears [[feather bonnet]] instead of a Glengarry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.courant.com/sdut-10000-marines-80000-spectators-expected-saturday-2003oct19-story.html?outputType=amp|title=10,000 Marines, 80,000 spectators expected Saturday for parade}}</ref>\n\n=== Band of America's Few ===\nCreated in 2009, the Band of America\u2019s Few is a nonprofit USMC musical unit organized by Marine retirees and veterans. Most of the musicians were assigned to the Marine Corps field bands in the past.<ref>http://bandofamericasfew.com/about-2/</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[United States military bands]]\n* [[Fleet Band Activities]]\n* [[List of United States Air Force bands]]\n* [[Navy bands in Canada]]\n* [[Royal Marines Band Service]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{US Marine Corps navbox}}\n{{United States military bands|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Bands of the United States Marine Corps]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toNew York(link changed toNew York City) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marine_Corps_Musician_Enlistment_Option_Program"}
{"title_page": "Jimi Behringer", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name = Jimi Behringer\n| website = \n| style = {{Flatlist|\n* Rock\n* Blues\n* R&B\n* Funk\n* Jazz\n}}\n| birth_place = [[Minneapolis]], Minnesota, United States\n| birth_name = James Thomas Behringer\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1953|07|19}}\n}}\n\n'''James Thomas''' \"'''Jimi'''\" '''Behringer''' (born July 19, 1953) is an American session guitarist, singer and songwriter. He has worked with notable artists such as [[Prince (musician)|Prince]], [[Bonnie Raitt]], [[Bobby Caldwell]], [[Laura Branigan]], [[The Jets (Minnesota band)|The Jets]], [[Ben Sidran]], [[Willie Murphy (musician)|Willie Murphy]], 94 East, [[Gypsy (band)|Gypsy]], [[Kitar\u014d]] and [[Jeff Lorber]].\n\nHe is a co-writer on Caldwell's ''August Moon'' album and was included as a session guitarist on the Prince single \"[[The Most Beautiful Girl in the World (Prince song)|The Most Beautiful Girl In The World]]\".<ref name=princevault>{{Cite web|url=https://www.princevault.com/index.php?title=The_Most_Beautiful_Girl_In_The_World|title=The Most Beautiful Girl In The World - Prince Vault|website=www.princevault.com|access-date=2020-02-03}}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\nJames was born in Minneapolis, Minnesota to Joan Patricia Sullivan and Cecil Richard Behringer. He began playing guitar at the age of 10 and performed in his older brother's band and local neighborhood bands.  His father was a renowned inventor<ref>{{Cite patent|title=Fire fighting airplane|gdate=1956-09-22|url=https://patents.google.com/patent/US2895693A/en}}</ref> and metallurgist who worked and consulted for aerospace and engineering firms.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://minnesota.cbslocal.com/2015/06/22/guy-on-a-bike-remembering-cecil-behringer/|title=Guy On A Bike: Remembering Cecil Behringer|date=2015-06-22|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref>  The two collaborated to create Behringer Bicycles after he convinced Cecil, a champion six day bike racer during the [[Great Depression]], to create modern race bicycles using cutting edge manufacturing methods his father was developing in the mid 1970s.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=R9kDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA79&lpg=PA79&dq=cecil+behringer&source=bl&ots=RygouNIpmn&sig=ACfU3U1LqRBGnJwOvi9uje8EPaqqcH-p-w&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjeo7no4bHnAhXVLs0KHVxUD-Q4ChDoATABegQICBAB#v=onepage&q=cecil%20behringer&f=false|title=Popular Mechanics|last=Magazines|first=Hearst|date=July 1982|publisher=Hearst Magazines|language=en}}</ref>  James decided after several years working at Behringer Bicycles to pursue his passion of music.\n\n== Career ==\nHe began his professional career working with the local Minneapolis band, Good Vibrations.  After leaving Good Vibrations, he joined [[Gypsy (band)|The James Walsh Gypsy Band]].  He became the lead guitarist and cowriter for the group, going on to record two albums, including the recently released ''Muscle Shoals'' album.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gypsy-queen.net/muscleshoals.html|title=Gypsy - Muscle Shoals|website=www.gypsy-queen.net|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/artist/412304-James-Walsh-Gypsy-Band|title=James Walsh Gypsy Band|website=Discogs|language=en|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref>\n\nMoving to Florida after Gypsy disbanded, he was introduced to [[Bobby Caldwell]] by a radio DJ who had heard Behringer's demo tapes.  Caldwell invited him to join in writing his new album and they spent two years recording ''August Moon'', which was critically well received in Japan and went on to receive Gold certification.{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\nIn 1984 he was hired to work with the platinum selling artist [[Laura Branigan]] as a guitarist and background singer on her [[Self Control (album)|''Self Control'']] album tour. Touring with Branigan brought him to perform on ''[[The Tonight Show Starring Johnny Carson]]'',<ref>{{Citation|title=Laura Branigan - \"Ti Amo\" LIVE [cc] The Tonight Show 1985 (Part 1 of 2)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=t5OddDDiA0I|language=en|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Laura Branigan - The Lucky One LIVE [cc] - The Tonight Show (1984)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zlZ2vNR0QzM|language=en|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref> and to a live performance recording at Caesars Tahoe.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.laurabraniganonline.com/main/dsg/dsg_conc_01.php|title=LauraBraniganOnline.com - The Official Laura Branigan Website - Discography|website=www.laurabraniganonline.com|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref>\n\n[[Jeff Lorber]] heard Behringer perform with Branigan and offered to hire him as a lead guitarist and background singer for Lorbers' upcoming Facts Of Love tour.  Once the Lorber tour was completed Behringer spent some time writing his own songs and built his first home recording studio.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://jefflorberfansite.blog29.fc2.com/blog-entry-101.html|title=Jeff Lorber Japanese fansite, by fans, for fans... {{!}}Karyn White performs \"Facts of Love\" with Jeff Lorber (1986)|website=jefflorberfansite.blog29.fc2.com|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref>\n\nIn 1988, Behringer was hired to perform on tour with the Japanese new age artist [[Kitar\u014d|Kitaro]].  The tour was to promote ''The Light of the Spirit'' album and was the first time an American band was used to back a Japanese artist.  Behringer found himself surrounded by an array of talented musicians ranging from [[Mahavishnu Orchestra]] members to veteran session musicians in the industry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.muzines.co.uk/articles/kitaro/4554|title=Kitaro (SOS May 89)|website=www.muzines.co.uk|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref>\n\nBetween tours, he was working as a session musician in his hometown of Minneapolis, regularly working with top producers and artists.  In 1994, Behringer was brought in as a session musician on the top 10 [[Prince (musician)|Prince]] single \"[[The Most Beautiful Girl in the World (Prince song)|The Most Beautiful Girl In The World]]\".\n\n== Discography ==\n* ''[https://www.discogs.com/artist/412304-James-Walsh-Gypsy-Band James Walsh Gypsy Band]''  (RCA Records, 1978)\n* ''[https://www.discogs.com/artist/412304-James-Walsh-Gypsy-Band James Walsh Gypsy Band] \"Muscle Shoals 1979\"'' (Gypsy Family Productions, 2008)\n* ''[[Bobby Caldwell]] [https://www.discogs.com/Bobby-Caldwell-August-Moon/release/8946183 \"August Moon\"]'' (PolyGram Records, 1983)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Bobby-Caldwell-August-Moon/release/8946183|title=Bobby Caldwell - August Moon|website=Discogs|language=en|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref>\n* ''[[The Jets (Minnesota band)|The Jets \"The Jets\"]]'' (Grammy Nomination) (MCA Records, 1985)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afmsagaftrafund.org/covered-artist-all_SR_20190430.php?p=d4ZkStOhQIOEWzrFHRkRLFeGoaEUJo0qgSvknKOmQms&n=nAh3d_Co4Y1gplJXlfeh6yhcKbPdj3ASDyn28z4LAio|title=Covered Recordings Title {{!}} Sound Recording {{!}} AFM SAG AFTRA|website=www.afmsagaftrafund.org|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref>\n* ''[[Willie Murphy (musician)|Willie Murphy]] [https://www.discogs.com/Willie-Murphy-Mr-Mature/release/2103694 \"Mr. Mature\"]'' (Atomic Theory Records, 1988)\n* ''[https://www.allmusic.com/artist/steve-kindler-mn0000027541 Steve Kindler] [https://www.discogs.com/Steve-Kindler-Across-A-Rainbow-Sea/release/4849639 \"Across A Rainbow Sea\"]''  (Global Pacific Records, 1990)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Steve-Kindler-Across-A-Rainbow-Sea/release/4849639|title=Steve Kindler* - Across A Rainbow Sea|website=Discogs|language=en|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref>\n* ''[[Felton Pilate]]/MC Hammer Project'' (Paisley Park, 1990)\n* ''[https://www.rickypeterson.com/ Ricky Peterson] [https://www.discogs.com/Ricky-Peterson-Night-Watch/release/5270048 \"Night Watch\"]'' (Warner Brothers Records, 1990)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bensidran.com/production/night-watch|title=Night Watch / Ricky Peterson {{!}} Production {{!}} Ben Sidran|last=Sidran|first=Ben|website=bensidran|language=en|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref>\n* ''[[Jevetta Steele]] [https://musicanaveia2210.wordpress.com/2016/05/19/jevetta-steele-here-it-is/ \"Here It Is\"]'' (Uno Musique Musidisc, 1991)\n* ''[[Doctor Fink|Dr. Fink]] and the Mystery Band  \"[https://www.discogs.com/Dr-Fink-And-The-Mystery-Band-Hooked-On-A-Beatles-Tribute/release/999009 Hooked On A Beatles Tribute\"]''  (K Tel Records, 1992)\n* NBC Movie ''The Keys''  (1992)\n* ''[https://www.rickypeterson.com/ Ricky Peterson] [https://www.discogs.com/Ricky-Peterson-Smile-Blue/release/4464737 \"Smile Blue\"]''  (Go Jazz Records, 1992)\n* ''The Steeles [https://www.discogs.com/The-Steeles-Heaven-Help-Us-All/master/570539 \"Heaven Help Us All\"]''  (Electra Musician, 1993)\n* ''Jimi Behringer [https://www.discogs.com/Jimi-Behringer-Band-Think-2-much/release/11406979 \"Think 2 Much\"]''  (DieselRocker Records, 1994)\n* ''Jimmy McGriff \"McGriff Blues\"'' (K Tel, 1994)\n* ''[[Prince (musician)|Prince]] [[The Gold Experience|\"Gold Experience\"]]''  (Warner Brothers NPG Records, 1995)<ref name=princevault/>\n* ''[[Rosie Gaines|Rosie Gains]] [https://www.discogs.com/Rosie-Gaines-Closer-Than-Close/release/7415085 \"Closer Than Close\"]''  (Motown Records, 1995)\n* ''[https://www.rickypeterson.com/ Ricky Peterson] [https://www.discogs.com/Ricky-Peterson-A-Tear-Can-Tell/release/3797399 \"A Tear Can Tell\"]''  (Go Jazz Records, 1995)\n* ''[http://bensidran.com/production/solita Clementine/Ben Sidran  \"Solita\"]'' (GoJazz Records, 1996)\n* ''France Gall \"Message Personnel\"'' (Warner Music France, 1996)\n* ''Jimi Behringer [https://www.allmusic.com/album/livin-on-mars-mw0000671995 \"Livin' On Mars\"]'' (GoJazz Records, 1999)\n* ''[https://www.rickypeterson.com/ Ricky Peterson] [https://www.discogs.com/Ricky-Peterson-Souvenir/release/3379339 \"Souvenir\"]'' (Windham Hill Records, 1999)\n* ''[https://www.discogs.com/94-East-94-East-Featuring-1015-Fortune-Teller-Remix-With-Prince-On-Guitar/release/4713172 94 East \"Fortune Teller\"]'' Feat. Prince on guitar (Reo Deo Records, 2002)\n* ''Jimi Behringer \"[https://www.allmusic.com/album/expressed-mw0000710396/credits Expressed\"]'' (String Theory Digital Disc, 2005)\n* ''Jimi Behringer  [https://www.allmusic.com/album/dying-to-live-mw0000710392 \"Dying To Live\"]'' (String Theory Digital Disc, 2005)\n* ''[https://www.rickypeterson.com/ Ricky Peterson] \"Best Of. Vol 1&2\"''  (Celebration Records, 2009)\n* ''[[Rockie Robbins]] [https://www.discogs.com/Rockie-Robbins-Good-Life/release/13339947 \"Good Life\"]'' (Expansion Records, 2019)\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:American male guitarists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Minneapolis]]\n\n\n{{US-painter-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name = Jimi Behringer\n| website = \n| style = {{Flatlist|\n* Rock\n* Blues\n* R&B\n* Funk\n* Jazz\n}}\n| birth_place = [[Minneapolis]], Minnesota, United States\n| birth_name = James Thomas Behringer\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1953|07|19}}\n}}\n\n'''James Thomas''' \"'''Jimi'''\" '''Behringer''' (born July 19, 1953) is an American session guitarist, singer and songwriter. He has worked with notable artists such as [[Prince (musician)|Prince]], [[Bonnie Raitt]], [[Bobby Caldwell]], [[Laura Branigan]], [[The Jets (Minnesota band)|The Jets]], [[Ben Sidran]], [[Willie Murphy (musician)|Willie Murphy]], 94 East, [[Gypsy (band)|Gypsy]], [[Kitar\u014d]] and [[Jeff Lorber]]. \n\nHe is a co-writer on Caldwell's ''August Moon'' album and was included as a session guitarist on the Prince single \"[[The Most Beautiful Girl in the World (Prince song)|The Most Beautiful Girl In The World]]\".<ref name=princevault>{{Cite web|url=https://www.princevault.com/index.php?title=The_Most_Beautiful_Girl_In_The_World|title=The Most Beautiful Girl In The World - Prince Vault|website=www.princevault.com|access-date=2020-02-03}}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\nJames was born in Minneapolis, Minnesota to Joan Patricia Sullivan and Cecil Richard Behringer. He began playing guitar at the age of 10 and performed in his older brother's band and local neighborhood bands.  His father was a renowned inventor<ref>{{Cite patent|title=Fire fighting airplane|gdate=1956-09-22|url=https://patents.google.com/patent/US2895693A/en}}</ref> and metallurgist who worked and consulted for aerospace and engineering firms.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://minnesota.cbslocal.com/2015/06/22/guy-on-a-bike-remembering-cecil-behringer/|title=Guy On A Bike: Remembering Cecil Behringer|date=2015-06-22|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref>  The two collaborated together to create Behringer Bicycles after he convinced Cecil, a champion six day bike racer during the [[Great Depression]], to create modern race bicycles using cutting edge manufacturing methods his father was developing in the mid 1970s.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=R9kDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA79&lpg=PA79&dq=cecil+behringer&source=bl&ots=RygouNIpmn&sig=ACfU3U1LqRBGnJwOvi9uje8EPaqqcH-p-w&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjeo7no4bHnAhXVLs0KHVxUD-Q4ChDoATABegQICBAB#v=onepage&q=cecil%20behringer&f=false|title=Popular Mechanics|last=Magazines|first=Hearst|date=July 1982|publisher=Hearst Magazines|language=en}}</ref>  James decided after several years working at Behringer Bicycles to pursue his passion of music. \n\n== Career ==\nHe began his professional career working with the local Minneapolis band, Good Vibrations.  After leaving Good Vibrations, he joined [[Gypsy (band)|The James Walsh Gypsy Band]].  He became the lead guitarist and cowriter for the group, going on to record two albums, including the recently released ''Muscle Shoals'' album.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gypsy-queen.net/muscleshoals.html|title=Gypsy - Muscle Shoals|website=www.gypsy-queen.net|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/artist/412304-James-Walsh-Gypsy-Band|title=James Walsh Gypsy Band|website=Discogs|language=en|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref>\n\nMoving to Florida after Gypsy disbanded, he was introduced to [[Bobby Caldwell]] by a radio DJ who had heard Behringer's demo tapes.  Caldwell invited him to join in writing his new album and they spent two years recording ''August Moon'', which was critically well received in Japan and went on to receive Gold certification.{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\nIn 1984 he was hired to work with the platinum selling artist [[Laura Branigan]] as a guitarist and background singer on her [[Self Control (album)|''Self Control'']] album tour. Touring with Branigan brought him to perform on ''[[The Tonight Show Starring Johnny Carson]]'',<ref>{{Citation|title=Laura Branigan - \"Ti Amo\" LIVE [cc] The Tonight Show 1985 (Part 1 of 2)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=t5OddDDiA0I|language=en|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Laura Branigan - The Lucky One LIVE [cc] - The Tonight Show (1984)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zlZ2vNR0QzM|language=en|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref> and to a live performance recording at Caesars Tahoe.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.laurabraniganonline.com/main/dsg/dsg_conc_01.php|title=LauraBraniganOnline.com - The Official Laura Branigan Website - Discography|website=www.laurabraniganonline.com|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref>\n\n[[Jeff Lorber]] heard Behringer perform with Branigan and offered to hire him as a lead guitarist and background singer for Lorbers' upcoming Facts Of Love tour.  Once the Lorber tour was completed Behringer spent some time writing his own songs and built his first home recording studio.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://jefflorberfansite.blog29.fc2.com/blog-entry-101.html|title=Jeff Lorber Japanese fansite, by fans, for fans... {{!}}Karyn White performs \"Facts of Love\" with Jeff Lorber (1986)|website=jefflorberfansite.blog29.fc2.com|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref>\n\nIn 1988, Behringer was hired to perform on tour with the Japanese new age artist [[Kitar\u014d|Kitaro]].  The tour was to promote ''The Light of the Spirit'' album and was the first time an American band was used to back a Japanese artist.  Behringer found himself surrounded by an array of talented musicians ranging from [[Mahavishnu Orchestra]] members to veteran session musicians in the industry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.muzines.co.uk/articles/kitaro/4554|title=Kitaro (SOS May 89)|website=www.muzines.co.uk|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref>\n\nBetween tours, he was working as a session musician in his hometown of Minneapolis, regularly working with top producers and artists.  In 1994, Behringer was brought in as a session musician on the top 10 [[Prince (musician)|Prince]] single \"[[The Most Beautiful Girl in the World (Prince song)|The Most Beautiful Girl In The World]]\".\n\n== Discography ==\n* ''[https://www.discogs.com/artist/412304-James-Walsh-Gypsy-Band James Walsh Gypsy Band]''  (RCA Records, 1978)\n* ''[https://www.discogs.com/artist/412304-James-Walsh-Gypsy-Band James Walsh Gypsy Band] \"Muscle Shoals 1979\"'' (Gypsy Family Productions, 2008)\n* ''[[Bobby Caldwell]] [https://www.discogs.com/Bobby-Caldwell-August-Moon/release/8946183 \"August Moon\"]'' (PolyGram Records, 1983)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Bobby-Caldwell-August-Moon/release/8946183|title=Bobby Caldwell - August Moon|website=Discogs|language=en|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref>\n* ''[[The Jets (Minnesota band)|The Jets \"The Jets\"]]'' (Grammy Nomination) (MCA Records, 1985)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afmsagaftrafund.org/covered-artist-all_SR_20190430.php?p=d4ZkStOhQIOEWzrFHRkRLFeGoaEUJo0qgSvknKOmQms&n=nAh3d_Co4Y1gplJXlfeh6yhcKbPdj3ASDyn28z4LAio|title=Covered Recordings Title {{!}} Sound Recording {{!}} AFM SAG AFTRA|website=www.afmsagaftrafund.org|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref>\n* ''[[Willie Murphy (musician)|Willie Murphy]] [https://www.discogs.com/Willie-Murphy-Mr-Mature/release/2103694 \"Mr. Mature\"]'' (Atomic Theory Records, 1988)\n* ''[https://www.allmusic.com/artist/steve-kindler-mn0000027541 Steve Kindler] [https://www.discogs.com/Steve-Kindler-Across-A-Rainbow-Sea/release/4849639 \"Across A Rainbow Sea\"]''  (Global Pacific Records, 1990)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Steve-Kindler-Across-A-Rainbow-Sea/release/4849639|title=Steve Kindler* - Across A Rainbow Sea|website=Discogs|language=en|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref>\n* ''[[Felton Pilate]]/MC Hammer Project'' (Paisley Park, 1990)\n* ''[https://www.rickypeterson.com/ Ricky Peterson] [https://www.discogs.com/Ricky-Peterson-Night-Watch/release/5270048 \"Night Watch\"]'' (Warner Brothers Records, 1990)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bensidran.com/production/night-watch|title=Night Watch / Ricky Peterson {{!}} Production {{!}} Ben Sidran|last=Sidran|first=Ben|website=bensidran|language=en|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref>\n* ''[[Jevetta Steele]] [https://musicanaveia2210.wordpress.com/2016/05/19/jevetta-steele-here-it-is/ \"Here It Is\"]'' (Uno Musique Musidisc, 1991)\n* ''[[Doctor Fink|Dr. Fink]] and the Mystery Band  \"[https://www.discogs.com/Dr-Fink-And-The-Mystery-Band-Hooked-On-A-Beatles-Tribute/release/999009 Hooked On A Beatles Tribute\"]''  (K Tel Records, 1992)\n* NBC Movie ''The Keys''  (1992)\n* ''[https://www.rickypeterson.com/ Ricky Peterson] [https://www.discogs.com/Ricky-Peterson-Smile-Blue/release/4464737 \"Smile Blue\"]''  (Go Jazz Records, 1992)\n* ''The Steeles [https://www.discogs.com/The-Steeles-Heaven-Help-Us-All/master/570539 \"Heaven Help Us All\"]''  (Electra Musician, 1993)\n* ''Jimi Behringer [https://www.discogs.com/Jimi-Behringer-Band-Think-2-much/release/11406979 \"Think 2 Much\"]''  (DieselRocker Records, 1994)\n* ''Jimmy McGriff \"McGriff Blues\"'' (K Tel, 1994)\n* ''[[Prince (musician)|Prince]] [[The Gold Experience|\"Gold Experience\"]]''  (Warner Brothers NPG Records, 1995)<ref name=princevault/>\n* ''[[Rosie Gaines|Rosie Gains]] [https://www.discogs.com/Rosie-Gaines-Closer-Than-Close/release/7415085 \"Closer Than Close\"]''  (Motown Records, 1995)\n* ''[https://www.rickypeterson.com/ Ricky Peterson] [https://www.discogs.com/Ricky-Peterson-A-Tear-Can-Tell/release/3797399 \"A Tear Can Tell\"]''  (Go Jazz Records, 1995)\n* ''[http://bensidran.com/production/solita Clementine/Ben Sidran  \"Solita\"]'' (GoJazz Records, 1996)\n* ''France Gall \"Message Personnel\"'' (Warner Music France, 1996)\n* ''Jimi Behringer [https://www.allmusic.com/album/livin-on-mars-mw0000671995 \"Livin' On Mars\"]'' (GoJazz Records, 1999)\n* ''[https://www.rickypeterson.com/ Ricky Peterson] [https://www.discogs.com/Ricky-Peterson-Souvenir/release/3379339 \"Souvenir\"]'' (Windham Hill Records, 1999)\n* ''[https://www.discogs.com/94-East-94-East-Featuring-1015-Fortune-Teller-Remix-With-Prince-On-Guitar/release/4713172 94 East \"Fortune Teller\"]'' Feat. Prince on guitar (Reo Deo Records, 2002)\n* ''Jimi Behringer \"[https://www.allmusic.com/album/expressed-mw0000710396/credits Expressed\"]'' (String Theory Digital Disc, 2005)\n* ''Jimi Behringer  [https://www.allmusic.com/album/dying-to-live-mw0000710392 \"Dying To Live\"]'' (String Theory Digital Disc, 2005)\n* ''[https://www.rickypeterson.com/ Ricky Peterson] \"Best Of. Vol 1&2\"''  (Celebration Records, 2009)\n* ''[[Rockie Robbins]] [https://www.discogs.com/Rockie-Robbins-Good-Life/release/13339947 \"Good Life\"]'' (Expansion Records, 2019)\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:American male guitarists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Minneapolis]]\n\n\n{{US-painter-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Nat965", "label": "safe", "comment": "ApplyGen fix(es),typo(s) fixed: collaborated together \u2192 collaborated", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.or